Here, you'd want to escalate errors in the bodies before evaluating subsequent ones (and you can also avoid using a Vec by using an Option) e.g.:

```rust
let mut last_result = none;
for body in args[1..].iter() {
  body_result = eval(&body, env, &inner_context)?;
  last_result.replace(body_result);
}

last_result
  .ok_or_err(UncheckedError::InvalidArguments("Must pass at least 1 body to (let ...)".to_string()).into())
```

This way, if an arithmetic error or an `expects!` occurred in the first body the subsequent bodies _won't be processed_, which is probably what we want. We should add a test case for this behavior (and possibly a note in the documentation for `let`).

