Using this identifier to let others (Drawable) know that the Coordinator has changed, is an interesting pattern.

Alternatively, another way is to have Coordinator keep track of 'listeners', and notify them when specific things (scale, viewBoxRect, etc) change.  e.g.
```ts
// coordinator
enum EventType {
  ViewCoordinatesChanged,
}

addListener(eventType: EventType, callback: Function) {}
dispatchEvent(eventType: EventType) {}

setXScale() {
  this.dispatchEvent(EventType.ViewCoordinatesChanged);
}


// drawable
this.coordinator.addListener(ViewCoordinatesChanged, () => {
  this.isDirty = true;
});

setData(data) {
  this.isDirty = true;              // no need for clearIdentifier() complexity!
  this.rawSeriesData = data;
}

```

With events, it is
- easy to reason about who cares when the Coordinator changes
- easy to add new things that listen for Coordinator updates, instead of comparing identifiers
- easy to add more granular events later; if we wanted to distinguish XScale changes from YScale changes, Events.XScaleChanged + Events.YScaleChanged is simpler than making all listeners do `xScaleIdentifier !== prevXScaleIdentifier` + `yScaleIdentifier !== prevYScaleIdentifier`

